      "content": "MACRS depreciation for a 7-year property class, you say? That's a bit of a long-term investment, isn't it? I can see why you'd want to calculate the depreciation correctly. \n\nThe MACRS formula is a bit complex, but I'll break it down for you. The formula for the first year is: \n\nYear 1 Depreciation = Cost of Equipment - Residual Value / 7\n\nHowever, since you didn't provide the cost and residual value, I'll assume you know those. The rate for the first year is 100% of the cost, but that's just the beginning. You'll need to apply the MACRS rates for each subsequent year, which are as follows: \n\nYear 2: 16.67%\nYear 3: 25%\nYear 4: 16.67%\nYear 5: 25%\nYear 6: 16.67%\nYear 7: 25%\n\nKeep in mind that these rates are based on the Modified Accelerated Cost Recovery System (MACRS) for a 7-year property class. It's a bit like a treasure hunt, but with tax deductions instead of treasure. You'll need to calculate the depreciation for each",
